About
Step on board this iconic London landmark. Navigate your way around the rooms of this floating city, climbing up and down ladders to visit all nine decks. You’ll hear stories from the 950 people who lived and served on the ship, which had its own chapel, radio station and bakery and is so large you can almost lie Big Ben across its deck – twice! IWM members go free.

  • Ladyofcampfires
    Aylesbury, United Kingdom66 contributions
    Very interesting visit
    We visited HMS Belfast on our final day in London, as it was more out of the way from our hotel room we decided to do this in the morning and head off to the train station to go home from there. We visited a number of museums during our stay, including others owned by IWM and, going off of these experiences, we expected there to be lockers here. There are none. It is the one attraction that nearly needs them due to the small spaces and various ladders to climb and doing this whilst carrying our luggage was...an experience. So don't make the same mistake we did! It is, however a fascinating visit. It takes a lot longer to walk around than I was expecting and is so much bigger inside than you would perhaps imagine. Not everyday you get to step onboard a war ship so it was really interesting and I learned a lot. The lower decks feel a bit claustrophobic so that might not be for everyone but all in all, really fascinating visit I imagine people of all ages and all interest levels in the subject would enjoy. There's toilets, cafe and gift shop too so the usual amenities can be found even though you're on a ship and there's lovely views of tower bridge from the deck to. The visit here was more for my partner but I thoroughly enjoyed it much more than I thought I would and I would highly recommend it.

Solihull, UK44 contributions
Outstanding, hands-on experience
Nov 2024 • Family
HMS Belfast is a unique opportunity to get into the bowels of a WW2 ship. Location is conveniently central in London, and once on board it didn't feel too crowded (despite the bedlam on the river bank) so you had plenty of time to move around the ship and look at everything at your leisure. Lots of ladders, many of which are narrow and steep - this is not for those with mobility needs at all. Younger children should be fine and will love climbing around. Great crowd control - the ship is big enough that it never felt oversold. Some members of the party enjoyed the audio guides but others got on fine without.
Enjoy some fantastic views of the city and Tower Bridge from the decks.
Highly recommended, and an attraction you may want to visit multiple times. Only slight quibble is that it's so open and self guided that you may worry you've missed bits despite the map you receive - a more concrete route may be helpful especially as various sections are, by necessity, one way.
Fantastic!
Written November 11, 2024

This is the best museum I have been to in London. The HMS Belfast is an incredible piece of history. I was completely captured by all the rooms and areas available to view. Paul E
Derby, UK542 contributions
Immersive!
Sep 2024 • Family
Wow, an absolutely amazing experience for myself and my 7 yr old daughter. I was worried she wouldn't enjoy it, as it's more my thing but we decided to use my IWM membership and have a look.
The view from outside doesn't give the true impression about how vast it is and you easily need 2 hours to see everything, 3 if engrossed in it. We were lucky it wasn't particularly busy when we arrived and there are some amazing opportunities to photograph the area as well as many many different parts of the ship.
You get very easily immersed in the rich history of the ship across all 9 decks! Moving around the place isn't for the less-mobile but part of the appeal for both of us was the clambering up and down ladders, through doors and into different sections! There's a free audio guide to take around with you, though we didn't on this occasion as we wanted to just explore on our own. All the staff from shop to on board volunteers were excellent, friendly and helpful.
Written September 1, 2024
